An if statement, also known as a conditional statement, is a programming construct used to evaluate a condition and perform an action based on whether the condition is true or false. It's like a rule that you can use to control the flow of your code.

Here's a simple example of an if statement:

```
if (my_variable == 10) {
    // do something
}
```

In this example, the code will only run if the variable `my_variable` is equal to 10. If it's not, the code will skip over it.

If you want to add an else block, you can do so like this:

```
if (my_variable == 10) {
    // do something
} else {
    // do something else
}
```

This will run the code in the else block if the condition is false.

If you want to make the condition more complex, you can use a switch statement:

```
switch (my_variable) {
    case 10:
        // do something
    case 20:
        // do something else
    default:
        // do something else
